.This was dueto the fact that the LaserWriter driver was looking for a style mapping table in thefirst GevenaÔFONDÕ it found.  This is the one in the system file, which does not have a style mappingtable.Because it does not find a style mapping table, it tries to download a bitmapped font.Instead, theLaserWriter driver should look for another Geneva ÔFONDÕ.The LaserWriter driver has been changed to call the new routine GetNextFOND to look foranotherÔFONDÕ for the same family if the ÔFONDÕ it has does not have a style mapping table.With this fix,MacWrite II can print itÕs ReadMe document without any problems, whereas it would printinCourier without the fix.GetNextFOND also has code which checks to see if the ÔFONDÕ is in an override map.  If itis,GetNextFOND will search for the map after the first non-override map after the overridemap, sothat the same ÔFONDÕ resource will not be returned all the time.  To test this, I placeda copy ofthe Geneve ÔFONDÕ, and the ÔNFNTÕs in the System into a Gibbly and tried to print theReadMe file.This also printed correctly.----------------------------------------------------------¥----------------------------------------------------------5/27/92 6:43:18 PMFile: DictionaryEqu.a,1Owner: hae-sung Kim     Project: MainProjºInterfacesºAIncludesºFile: SysErr.a,36Owner: hae-sung Kim     Project: MainProjºInterfacesºAIncludesºFile: Traps.a,77Owner: hae-sung Kim     Project: MainProjºInterfacesºAIncludesºFile: Dictionary.h,1Owner: hae-sung Kim     Project: MainProjºInterfacesºCIncludesºFile: Errors.h,19Owner: hae-sung Kim     Project: MainProjºInterfacesºCIncludesºFile: Dictionary.p,1Owner: hae-sung Kim     Project: MainProjºInterfacesºPInterfacesºFile: Errors.p,21Owner: hae-sung Kim     Project: MainProjºInterfacesºPInterfacesºRadar bug: #1030902> Release notes for this change:Make new interface files for Dictionary manager.  Add Dictionary manager error numbers.> What was tested